ElementDescription: Fear of situation is due to thoughts that escape might be difficult, help may not be available, or other incapacitating symptoms (e.g. incontinence) (Current) - Child: Do you feel this way because it might be difficult to escape ___, or that you may not be able to get help if you need it?
Agoraphobic situation almost always provokes anxiety (Current) - Child: How often does ___ make you feel afraid, anxious, or upset
Situations avoided or required the presence of companion or endured with marked distress (Current) - Child: Do you avoid ___ or only go to ___ if someone is able to go with you?
The fear or anxiety is out of proportion to the danger posed by the situation (Current) - Child: Did you think other people your age have the same fears?
Significant distress or impairment with family, in school, or with peers (Current) - Child: How does this or has this affected your life? In school? With family? With friends?
Durations six months or longer (Current) - Child: How long have you felt fear involving ___?

Evidence of precipitant (Current) - Parent: Was there a situation that happened before that might have prompted these feelings in your child? Child: Did something happen before you started feeling this way? Do you think something caused you to fear ___?
Specify precipitant (Current)
Marked fear or anxiety: Using public transportation (e.g., automobiles, buses, trains, ships, planes)
Marked fear or anxiety: Being in open spaces (e.g., parking lots, marketplaces, bridges)
Marked fear or anxiety: Being in closed spaces (e.g., shops, theaters, or cinemas)
Marked fear or anxiety: Standing in line or being in a crowd
Marked fear or anxiety: Being outside of the home alone
Summary Score - Marked fear or anxiety - Current
Does the participant meet Criterion A - Marked fear or anxiety about two (or more) of the following five situations - Current

Does the participant meet Criterion B - Individual fears or avoids situations because of thoughts that escape might be difficult or help might not be available in the event of developing panic-like symptoms, or other incapacitating or embarrassing symptoms - Current
Does the participant meet Criterion C - Agoraphobic situations almost always provoke fear or anxiety - Current
Does the participant meet Criterion D - Situations are actively avoided, require the presence of a companion, or are endured with intense fear or anxiety - Current
Does the participant meet Criterion E - The fear or anxiety is out of proportion to the danger posed by the situation and the socio-cultural context - Current
Does the participant meet Criterion F - Duration of six months or longer - Current
Does the participant meet Criterion G - Significant distress or impairment in social, academic, occupational, or other important areas of functioning - Current
Does the participant meet Criterion H - If another medical condition (e.g., inflammatory bowel disease) is present, the fear, anxiety, or avoidance is excessive - Current

Does the participant meet Criterion I - The fear, anxiety, or avoidance is not better explained by the symptoms of another mental disorder - for example, the symptoms are not confined to specific phobia, situational type; do not involve only social situations (as in social anxiety disorder); and are not related exclusively to obsessions (as in obsessive-compulsive disorder), perceived defects or flaws in physical appearance (as in body dysmorphic disorder), reminders of traumatic events (as in posttraumatic stress disorder), or fear of separation (as in separation anxiety disorder) - Current
